6.statement:
Given the polygons $P$ and $Q$ as shown in the grid below, cut $P$ into two polygons $P_1$ and $P_2$ such that, when pasted together differently, they form $Q$.\begin{figure}[H]\centering
\begin{asy}[width=0.9\textwidth]
import graph; size(16cm); real lsf=0.5; pen dps=linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10); defaultpen(dps); pen ds=black; real xmin=-2.05,xmax=15.10,ymin=-1.87,ymax=9.74; pen cqcqcq=rgb(0.75,0.75,0.75), zzttqq=rgb(0.6,0.2,0); draw((7,5)--(12,5)--(12,2)--(7,2)--cycle,zzttqq); draw((2,2)--(2,5)--(3,6)--(6,6)--(6,3)--(5,2)--cycle,zzttqq); /*grid*/ pen gs=linewidth(0.7)+cqcqcq+linetype("2 2"); real gx=1,gy=1;for(real i=ceil(xmin/gx)*gx;i<=floor(xmax/gx)*gx;i+=gx) draw((i,ymin)--(i,ymax),gs); for(real i=ceil(ymin/gy)*gy;i<=floor(ymax/gy)*gy;i+=gy) draw((xmin,i)--(xmax,i),gs);  draw((0,8)--(0,0)); draw((0,0)--(13,0)); draw((13,0)--(13,8)); draw((13,8)--(0,8)); draw((7,5)--(12,5),zzttqq); draw((12,5)--(12,2),zzttqq); draw((12,2)--(7,2),zzttqq); draw((7,2)--(7,5),zzttqq); draw((2,2)--(2,5),zzttqq); draw((2,5)--(3,6),zzttqq); draw((3,6)--(6,6),zzttqq); draw((6,6)--(6,3),zzttqq); draw((6,3)--(5,2),zzttqq); draw((5,2)--(2,2),zzttqq); dot((0,0),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((13,0),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((0,8),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((2,2),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((6,6),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((13,8),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((7,2),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((7,5),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((12,2),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((12,5),linewidth(1pt)+ds); label("$Q$",(8.42,2.56),NE*lsf,zzttqq); dot((5,2),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((6,3),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((2,5),linewidth(1pt)+ds); dot((3,6),linewidth(1pt)+ds); label("$P$",(4.65,2.74),NE*lsf,zzttqq); clip((xmin,ymin)--(xmin,ymax)--(xmax,ymax)--(xmax,ymin)--cycle);
\end{asy}
\end{figure}

3.statement:
Define a ``hook" to be a figure made up of six unit squares as shown below in the picture, or any of the figures obtained by applying rotations and reflections to this figure.\begin{figure}[H]\centering
\begin{asy}[width=0.9\textwidth]
unitsize(0.5 cm);draw((0,0)--(1,0));draw((0,1)--(1,1));draw((2,1)--(3,1));draw((0,2)--(3,2));draw((0,3)--(3,3));draw((0,0)--(0,3));draw((1,0)--(1,3));draw((2,1)--(2,3));draw((3,1)--(3,3));
\end{asy}
\end{figure}Determine all $m\times n$ rectangles that can  be covered without gaps and without overlaps with hooks such that\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]\item the rectangle is covered without gaps and without overlaps\item no part of a hook covers area outside the rectangle.\end{enumerate}
